ire, Dorset, Gloucestershire, Herefordshire, Northamptonshire, Shropshire, Somerset, Staffordshire, Wiltshire, and Yorkshire. Most of the placenames derive from Old English <i>horh</i> or <i>horu</i> ‘dirt, filth’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’, though some may have different origins, including Horton in Gloucestershire, which may derive from Old English <i>heorot</i> ‘hart, stag’ + <i>tūn</i>."],"variants":[{"name":"Hortin","meanings":["English: variant of   Horton  ."]},{"name":"Horten","meanings":["English: variant of   Horton  .","Norwegian: habitational name from any of several farms named Horten, from an unattested word denoting ‘uneven, hard and lumpy soil’."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["Formed from Margaret."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Margaret Horton was born in 1280, in Devon, England, United Kingdom. She had at least 1 daughter with William Hatch. She died in 1298, in England, United Kingdom, at the age of 18."},"et":{"1280–1298":"1280–1298","1278–1330":"1278–1330","1298–1371":"1298–1371","1278":"1278","1298":"1298","1330":"1330","1371":"1371","1280":"1280","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","South Moulton, Devon, England":"Devon, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Aller, Dorset, England":"Aller, Dorset, England"},"fi":{"1280–1298":"1280–1298","1278–1330":"1278–1330","1298–1371":"1298–1371","1278":"1278","1298":"1298","1330":"1330","1371":"1371","1280":"1280","England":"Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","South Moulton, Devon, England":"Devon, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Aller, Dorset, England":"Aller, Dorset, England"},"fr":{"1280–1298":"1280–1298","1278–1330":"1278–1330","1298–1371":"1298–1371","1278":"1278","1298":"1298","1330":"1330","1371":"1371","1280":"1280","England":"Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","South Moulton, Devon, England":"Devon, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","Aller, Dorset, England":"Aller, Dorset, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Margaret Horton est née en 1280, à Devon, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni. Elle a eu au moins 1 fille avec William Hatch. Elle est décédée en 1298, à Angleterre, Royaume-Uni, à l’âge de 18 ans."},"de":{"1280–1298":"1280–1298","1278–1330":"1278–1330","1298–1371":"1298–1371","1278":"1278","1298":"1298","1330":"1330","1371":"1371","1280":"1280","England":"England, United Kingdom","South Moulton, Devon, England":"Devon, England, United Kingdom","Aller, Dorset, England":"Aller, Dorset, England","lifeSummary":"Margaret Horton wurde 1280 in Devon, England, United Kingdom geboren. Sie hatte mit William Hatch mindestens 1 Tochter. Sie starb 1298 im Alter von 18 Jahren in England, United Kingdom."},"ht":{"1280–1298":"1280–1298","1278–1330":"1278–1330","1298–1371":"1298–1371","1278":"1278","1298":"1298","1330":"1330","1371":"1371","1280":"1280","Englan